data.content:
Here's what happened and how to fix it:

## The Problem

In C# 14, new built-in span conversions cause **overload resolution** to prefer `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` over `Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<T>, T)` when called on an array. `MemoryExtensions.Contains` **cannot be represented in a LINQ expression tree**, so it throws at runtime.

## The Fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` to force the compiler to bind to `Enumerable.Contains`:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three prevent the span overload from being selected, keeping the expression tree valid.
